My role
in this project

PetMind was a 4-person team project. This page documents my individual contributions — the work I personally owned from start to finish, and the design decisions I drove.

While the team collaborated across all phases, I took primary ownership of user research, user flows & wireframes, prototype design in Figma, and leading usability testing.

What I owned

  • 1
    Conducted user research & interviews — identified the core problem space
  • 2
    Built user flows & wireframes — defined how the app connects end-to-end
  • 3
    Created & iterated prototypes in Figma — all 3 design rounds
  • 4
    Led usability testing — designed protocols, ran sessions, synthesised findings
🎤

User Research & Interviews

I planned and conducted interviews with pet owners across experience levels — first-time owners, experienced owners, vets, and exotic pet keepers. I synthesised responses into three insight clusters that shaped the entire feature set: pet-centred issues, owner wellbeing, and family concerns.

Discovery · Synthesis · Insight generation
🗺️

User Flows & Wireframes

I mapped the full app architecture — from onboarding through daily recording to health reports. The wireframe work established how every screen connects, ensuring users always have clear context about where they are and what action to take next.

Information architecture · Low-fi wireframing
✦

Prototype Design in Figma

I created high-fidelity prototypes across all three design cycles — from the initial cartoonish concept through to the final orange-branded system with Rubik typography. Every screen in this portfolio is the output of that work, refined through real user feedback at each round.

High-fidelity design · Figma · 3 iterations
🔬

Usability Testing Lead

I designed the testing protocol, recruited participants, facilitated sessions, and wrote the observation report. Issues I directly observed — the confusing profile page, reminder friction, repetitive recording steps — became the concrete roadmap for our final iteration.

Test facilitation · Observation · Report writing

User Research

Who are we designing for —
and what did they tell us?

Before touching Figma, I led the research phase — defining target users, designing interview questions, collecting data, and translating findings into design decisions.

🎤
8+
User interviews conducted across different pet owner profiles
📋
3
Core insight clusters synthesised from raw interview data
🔄
3×
Rounds of usability testing — each directly informing the next iteration
How I gathered data
Step 1

Stakeholder Interviews

I conducted in-depth interviews with pet owners spanning different experience levels — first-time owners, experienced multi-pet households, vets, and exotic pet keepers. Questions focused on daily routines, pain points with existing tools, and health-related anxieties.

Key Findings

Text entry was the #1 barrier to daily logging — "I forget by the time I open the app"
Most users juggled 2–3 separate apps (calendar, notes, vet app) with no integration
Exotic pet owners felt completely underserved by existing tools
Step 2

Insight Synthesis

After interviews, I synthesised responses into an affinity map — clustering observations into three problem categories. These became the non-negotiable design pillars that every feature had to address before we could move to Figma.

3 Problem Clusters

Pet-Centred — owners need early visibility into health changes before they escalate
Owner Wellbeing — cognitive load of manual tracking creates anxiety, not peace of mind
Family Concerns — disease transmission and household impact for families with children
Step 3

Competitive Analysis

I analysed the two leading alternatives — PetDesk and Pawtrack — to identify gaps PetMind could fill. This grounded the feature prioritisation in market reality rather than assumptions.

Gaps Found

PetDesk: appointment-only, no daily health tracking or nutrition data
Pawtrack: GPS-only, no health records, no recommendations
Opportunity: integrated daily tracking + smart recommendations = unserved market
Step 4

Usability Testing (×3 rounds)

I designed the test protocol for all three rounds — scenario-based tasks, observation note sheets, and post-session debrief questions. I moderated sessions, took notes, and wrote the synthesis report after each round.

Testing Tasks Included

Record today's pet health data using only the app
Find where to set a feeding reminder
Add a new pet to the account
Locate the recommended food for today
From research insight → design decision
💬 "Text entry is too slow — I give up after day 3"
↓
Replaced all text inputs with tap-to-select multiple choice. Zero typing required in the core recording flow.
💬 "I forget to log because I need to open the app first"
↓
Central Record button on the home screen + push notification reminders + auto-timestamp on entry.
💬 "My reptile has completely different needs — no app supports that"
↓
Customisable recording categories + temperature & humidity widgets for exotic pet owners.
User Personas

Designing for real people,
not assumptions

Based on my interview findings, I synthesised two primary personas that guided every design decision — representing the two most distinct user archetypes we encountered.

Jason Miller, 41

Creative / Flexible
Freelance Illustrator · Austin, TX
Design impact
Jason's frustration with rigid tools validated our skip-any-step architecture. His need for lightweight admin reminders drove the in-app reminder system. His chaotic schedule justified the Catch-Up Record feature.

Lily Zhang, 29

Organised / Goal-driven
Product Manager · Shanghai
Design impact
Lily's need for clean visual organisation shaped our colour-coded health summary. Her pain point about fragmented platforms drove the all-in-one Records hub. Her perfectionism validated the exportable vet report feature.
Onboarding

Personalised
from the first tap

Pet setup in seconds

Icon-driven pet type selection (Cat, Dog, Exotic, Other) means users personalise the entire experience without typing a single word. The illustrated welcome screen immediately communicates PetMind's warmth — "Only for real friends."

  • Large tap targets — fast, error-free selection
  • Pet type personalises every subsequent screen
  • "I don't have a pet yet" — inclusive escape route

Choose what you track at signup

A key wireframing decision: surface the recording category selection during onboarding — not buried in settings. The daily recording flow is already tailored before users even start. Modifiable any time in My Pet.

  • Diet, Drinking, Sleeping, Health, Activity toggles
  • Reduces cognitive load for daily check-ins
  • Supports exotic owners with unique tracking needs
Core Feature

The Daily Recording Flow

Designed to complete in under 60 seconds. Every step uses tap-to-select. Any step can be skipped. A satisfying animation closes the loop.

Health Records

Data that tells a story

Dietary tracking & smart insights

Records hub spans Summary, Dietary, Drinking, Health, Activity, and Temperature & Humidity — each with time-series charts switchable between Day, Week, Month, and Year. Export directly as a veterinary report.

  • Trend charts with percentage change vs yesterday
  • Contextual nutrition tips per category
  • Export as veterinary report for vet consultations

Vaccination & medication tracking

Health rating (75%), full vaccination schedules (FeLV, Rabies, FVRCP), and deworming history — all in one view. Overdue items are clearly flagged in red so nothing gets missed.

  • Overdue alerts prominently surfaced
  • Full vaccination date log
  • Health score with circular progress indicator
Pet Profile

Everything about
your pet, in one place

Pet management & full customisation

KitKat's profile surfaces breed, age, weight, diet plans, and a direct path to health reports. Settings give users control over Record Customisation, Device Connection, Colour Theme, Notifications, and Dark Mode.

  • Smart device integration — 2 devices connected
  • Diet plan management with multi-plan switching
  • Colour theme customisable to owner preference
  • All editable in place — no buried menus
Design System

Visual language

A cohesive system ties every screen — high-contrast orange, Rubik typeface, and a clean light surface approachable for all ages and experience levels.

Design Principles

  • 44×44pt minimum tap targets
  • High-contrast orange for all lighting conditions
  • Icons supplement labels — usable without reading
  • One primary CTA per screen
  • Skip available on every optional step
Design Process

3 iterations,
evidence-based changes

Each prototype round was followed by usability testing I led. Every design change maps directly to a specific user observation — no guessing.

1

Iteration 1 — Cartoonish Draft

Lighthearted illustrated concept. Usability testing revealed users couldn't identify the app's core functions from the home screen, and low contrast made key elements hard to see.

❌ Unclear main functions❌ Low contrast❌ Vague button labels❌ Inconsistent palette
2

Iteration 2 — Structural Redesign

Rebuilt with a central Record button and auto-timestamping. New user flows redefined the navigation architecture to communicate purpose on first glance.

✓ Central record button✓ Auto timestamp✓ Clearer navigation❌ Visual inconsistency remained
3

Iteration 3 — Final High-Fidelity

Unified colour palette, Rubik throughout, tap-select recording with skip logic, and a completion animation. Addressed every friction point observed during my final usability testing round.

✓ Consistent orange system✓ Tap-select inputs✓ Skip any step✓ Completion animation✓ Smart recommendations
Usability Testing

What I found —
and what I'd change next

I designed the test protocol, moderated sessions, and wrote the observation report. These findings and recommendations are my own.

What I Observed

  • Clean layout and intuitive icons were praised — users navigated without guidance
  • All core tasks completed successfully in testing
  • Recording process felt too long for a daily habit
  • Profile page confused participants — owner vs pet account unclear
  • No visual confirmation of set reminders — required extra navigation

My Recommendations

  • Add a home screen reminder status indicator
  • Merge related questions — target <30 second completion
  • Visually distinguish pet profile from user account
  • Add habit streaks and micro-celebrations for daily retention
  • AI-personalise recording categories over time based on usage
